[2] China: Hubei
Date: Sun 13 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua/Reuters via China daily, 12 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-11/12/content_494135.htm>

China reports new bird flu outbreak in Hubei
-----------------------------------------------
China has confirmed a fresh outbreak of the deadly H5N1 bird flu
virus in poultry in its central Hubei province, the Hong Kong
government said on Saturday [12 Nov 2005], Reuters reported.
"The Health, Welfare and Food Bureau received notification from the
Ministry of Agriculture of the Mainland last night, of an H5N1 avian
influenza outbreak among poultry in Jingshan country in Hubei
province" the Hong Kong government said in a statement.
This latest outbreak comes as China is battling to control 7 other
outbreaks since the beginning [of] October 2005.
The Liaoning Provincial Control Office of Highly Pathogenic Avian
Flu, on Saturday [12 Nov 2005], ruled out 6 suspected highly
pathogenic bird flu outbreaks in this northeast China province. Zhou
Liyuan, spokesman for the office, told a press conference that the
judgment was concluded, as the quarantine tests conducted by the
provincial animal epidemic prevention station lab turned out negative
for highly pathogenic avian flu virus.
The office has erased Nanwa Village in Xinmin City of Shenyang,
Jintun Village of Jinzhou City, Bajiazi Village of Jinzhou, Guojia
Village of Jinzhou, the Beizhen Street of Beining City in Jinzhou and
Yujiatun Village of Heishan County from the bird flu blacklist.
In bird-flu-hit Heishan County, no new cases have been reported for
the last 2 days. In bird-flu-hit Beining City, no new cases have been
reported for the last 4 days. In Nanzhan New District of Jinzhou, no
new cases have been reported since 6 Nov 2005. In New Mongolia
Autonomous County of Fuxin City, no new cases have been reported
since 8 Nov 2005, all as listed by the spokesman.
He said that the provincial government has allocated 15.5 million
yuan (USD 1.9 million) to compensate the farmers for their loss due
to poultry culling. A total of 265.8 million yuan (USD 33 million)
has been put into epidemic prevention in the province.
Zhang Wenyue, governor of Liaoning Province, has pledged the
government would compensate farmers for every poultry head culled for
epidemic prevention. According to the province's compensation
standard, farmers are compensated with 10 yuan (USD 1.25) for each of
their chickens and ducks slaughtered in quarantine, 15 yuan (USD
1.87) for a goose and 5 yuan (USD 0.65) for every young fowl.
The spokesman said that hospitals in bird flu-hit areas in Liaoning
have been ordered to accept flu patients regardless of medical
charges, which will be later drawn from the provincial finances.
