[4] China
Date: Sun 13 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: China daily, 14 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2005-11/14/content_494232.htm>

Processed poultry: Strict checks ordered
---------------------------------------------
The nation's quality watchdog said yesterday [Sun 13 Nov 2005] that
it would check processed poultry to ensure that no birds come from
regions affected by bird flu, even as veterinary workers cull
hundreds of thousands of fowl to curb the spread of the disease.
The inspections will cover 16 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions.
It will also check the quality of disinfectants used for combating
bird flu, the General Administration of Quality Supervision,
Inspection and Quarantine of China said in a statement yesterday [13
Nov 2005].
Regions where inspectors will fan out include areas that have been
stricken by the fatal bird flu virus this year [2005]: Qinghai, Inner
Mongolia, Anhui, Hubei, Hunan and Liaoning, and 10 others, including
Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Hebei.
The efforts are to help protect the health and restore the confidence
of consumers, whose appetite for poultry has waned, according to
experts.
Quality supervisors will check the food production permits of poultry
product makers and impose tough penalties on firms which do not have
them.
In particular, inspectors will look for proof of the makers,
especially those in the vicinity of an outbreak site, to ensure that
the birds have been certified by quarantine authorities and that no
dead or sick chicken, ducks or geese were used, it said. Violators
will be dealt with severely.
The inspectors will also see to it that no fake or shoddy
disinfectants, such as bleaching powder, caustic soda or peractic
acid, enter the market.
In the Chinese capital, the municipal health bureau said on Saturday
[12 Nov 2005] that not a single case of human infection had been
detected after major hospitals in Beijing checked about 850 000
people.
In its latest effort to prevent bird flu, the city shut down and
disinfected an illegal pigeon fair in Beishatan on Saturday [12 Nov
2005].
In Northeast China's Liaoning Province, which reported its 1st case
of fatal bird flu on 3 Nov 2005, the provincial office handling the
disease gave the all-clear in 6 suspected outbreaks on Saturday [12
Nov 2005].
[Byline: Zhao Huanxin]
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The above 3 news items from China's media underline the severity
with which the authorities consider the situation. Typically, they
also claim the need to "restore the confidence of consumers, whose
appetite for poultry has waned, according to experts." Real-value
compensations to farmers for culled birds are essential if their
cooperation is sought; without such cooperation, no control program
will effectively work.
Another crucial issue is the control and certification of vaccines
and disinfectants. Clearly, there is ample room for improvement
thereof. A recent example, kindly forwarded by Martin Williams, is a
news item from today's (13 Nov 2005) South China Morning Post. It
reports the distribution of an unlicensed AI vaccine in Liaoning
province, smuggled from Inner Mongolia, where the producer allegedly
released it before completion of testing. Reportedly, this vaccine
"offered little protection against the deadly disease."
Enhanced law enforcement is essential, but this stick must go
hand-in-hand with the carrot of subsidizing certified, efficacious
preparations and biologicals in order to compete with illegal,
uncertified cheap ones of inferior quality. - Mod.AS]
